The survey underlined the religious conservatism in a largely Catholic steadied by Catholic social policy – such as the eventual adoption of same-sex marriage as the country’s lower house votes on Wednesday – and by population decline.

As part of an experiment with the decriminalisation of illegal abortions, launched in 1938, Uruguay has been more tolerant than other Latin American nations.

Planned parenthood in Montevideo’s central Parque Rodó | API

But the results of the latest study published by Lancet suggest a ‘major effort’ is needed to include women’s needs.

As opposed to a previous study on sexual and reproductive health in Uruguay which indicated that only 10% of men perceived abortion as a public health issue or a human right, the latest results found that 60% of the 599 men interviewed believed it to be a human right issue.

“That was a surprise to us,” said Mariana Albani, the study’s main responsible, a junior researcher at Montevideo’s Catholic University (Udelar).

SCARED

The participants were asked about their perception of the risks and morality of abortion in cases of rape, and for high-risk pregnancies, as a tool of population control. Almost half of the men surveyed supported incest legislation.
